@page "/ai-excel-formula-generator"
@inject ProductBranding Branding

<PageTitle>AI Excel Formula Generator and Formula Copilot - @Branding.SiteName</PageTitle>
<HeadContent>
    <meta name="description" content="Preview ExcelToolStack AI Formula Copilot for turning plain English into Excel formulas, explaining formulas, debugging spreadsheet logic, and working across Excel and Google Sheets." />
    <link rel="canonical" href="@($"{Branding.SiteUrl}/ai-excel-formula-generator")" />
    <meta property="og:title" content="@($"AI Excel Formula Generator and Formula Copilot - {Branding.SiteName}")" />
    <meta property="og:description" content="A public preview of an AI formula copilot for Excel formulas, Google Sheets formulas, explanations, debugging, and spreadsheet prompts." />
</HeadContent>

<section class="tool-hero">
    <div class="tool-hero-copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">AI Formula Copilot</p>
        <h1>Turn plain English into spreadsheet formulas with more confidence.</h1>
        <p class="lead">
            A premium landing page for the planned @Branding.SiteName formula copilot: generate Excel formulas,
            explain existing logic, debug broken formulas, and adapt patterns for Google Sheets.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions">
            <a class="button button--primary" href="/tools">Explore all tools</a>
            <a class="button button--secondary" href="/blog">Read spreadsheet guides</a>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-proof" aria-label="Formula Copilot capabilities">
            <span>Plain English to formula</span>
            <span>Formula explanation</span>
            <span>Formula debugging</span>
            <span>Excel and Google Sheets</span>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="copilot-console" aria-label="Non-functional AI formula copilot preview">
        <div class="console-header">
            <span>Formula request</span>
            <strong>Preview only</strong>
        </div>
        <label for="formulaPrompt">Describe the formula you need</label>
        <textarea id="formulaPrompt" disabled>Calculate commission when revenue in B2 is above 50000, using 8%, otherwise 3%.</textarea>

        <label for="formulaOutput">Suggested formula</label>
        <textarea id="formulaOutput" disabled>=IF(B2&gt;50000,B2*8%,B2*3%)</textarea>

        <button class="button button--primary" type="button" disabled>Generate formula</button>
        <p class="disabled-note">
            This preview is intentionally disabled. No prompt is sent, no AI provider is connected, and no workbook is processed.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section-shell section-shell--tight">
    <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Use cases</p>
        <h2>Designed for the moments where formulas slow the work down.</h2>
        <p>
            The planned copilot is positioned for everyday analysts, operators, founders, students, and teams who
            need clear spreadsheet logic without turning every task into a formula research session.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="workflow-steps">
        <article>
            <span>01</span>
            <h3>Plain English to Excel formula</h3>
            <p>Describe the goal, columns, conditions, and desired output before converting it into spreadsheet logic.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
            <span>02</span>
            <h3>Formula explanation</h3>
            <p>Break down formulas into human-readable steps so workbook owners can review logic before sharing.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
            <span>03</span>
            <h3>Formula debugging</h3>
            <p>Plan support for fixing syntax, mismatched ranges, nested conditions, lookup errors, and unclear references.</p>
        </article>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section-shell section-shell--accent">
    <div class="section-heading section-heading--split">
        <div>
            <p class="eyebrow">Examples</p>
            <h2>Example prompts for formula-heavy work.</h2>
            <p>These prompts are static examples for the public shell. They do not execute yet.</p>
        </div>
        <a class="text-link" href="/templates">Pair with templates</a>
    </div>
    <div class="prompt-grid">
        <article>
            <span>Sales</span>
            <p>Write an Excel formula that calculates tiered commission based on monthly revenue and region.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
            <span>Operations</span>
            <p>Build a formula that flags overdue tasks when status is open and the due date is before today.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
            <span>Finance</span>
            <p>Explain this nested IF formula and suggest a cleaner version using IFS or SWITCH.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
            <span>Cleanup</span>
            <p>Create a formula that extracts the domain from an email address and handles blank cells.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
            <span>Lookups</span>
            <p>Debug why my XLOOKUP returns #N/A when the lookup value appears in the source table.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
            <span>Sheets</span>
            <p>Convert this Excel formula into a Google Sheets-friendly version with equivalent behavior.</p>
        </article>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section-shell">
    <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Excel and Google Sheets</p>
        <h2>Built for spreadsheet logic, not one app silo.</h2>
        <p>
            The future tool is positioned for Excel-first workflows while acknowledging teams often move between
            Microsoft Excel and Google Sheets. Formula syntax, function availability, and collaboration habits can differ.
        </p>
    </div>
    <div class="category-grid">
        <article>
            <span class="category-kicker">Excel</span>
            <h3>Business-grade workbook formulas</h3>
            <p>Support planned for common Excel logic patterns including lookups, conditional logic, dates, and summaries.</p>
            <a href="/tools">See tool categories</a>
        </article>
        <article>
            <span class="category-kicker">Google Sheets</span>
            <h3>Cloud spreadsheet variations</h3>
            <p>Positioned to help with Sheets-compatible formulas where functions, separators, or array behavior differ.</p>
            <a href="/blog">Read workflow guides</a>
        </article>
        <article>
            <span class="category-kicker">Review</span>
            <h3>Explain before you ship</h3>
            <p>Formula explanation and debugging are planned as first-class workflows for trust and handoff.</p>
            <a href="/pricing">View launch preview</a>
        </article>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section-shell section-shell--accent">
    <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">FAQ</p>
        <h2>AI Formula Copilot questions.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-grid">
        <article>
            <h3>Can this page generate formulas today?</h3>
            <p>No. This is a public landing page and disabled UI preview only. No AI provider or backend processing is connected.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
            <h3>Will it work for both Excel and Google Sheets?</h3>
            <p>The product positioning covers both Excel and Google Sheets, with Excel as the primary spreadsheet workflow surface.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
            <h3>Can it explain an existing formula?</h3>
            <p>Formula explanation is a planned workflow so users can understand nested logic, lookups, ranges, and conditions.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
            <h3>Will users need an account?</h3>
            <p>This page is anonymous and crawlable. No authentication, billing, or gated behavior has been added for this PR.</p>
        </article>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="cta-section">
    <p class="eyebrow">Tool preview</p>
    <h2>Explore the formula copilot inside the broader ExcelToolStack shell.</h2>
    <p>
        The first tool landing page now has a public route, static placeholder UI, SEO metadata, and links into the
        planned tools, templates, guides, and pricing surfaces.
    </p>
    <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="button button--primary" href="/tools">Back to tools</a>
        <a class="button button--secondary" href="/">Return home</a>
    </div>
</section>
